HEADWORD: djinny
<hw>djin"ny</hw></mhw>
<pr>(j⟦icr⟧n"n⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>djinn</plw> <pr>(j⟦icr⟧n)</pr> or <plw>djinns</plw>
<pr>(j⟦icr⟧nz)</pr>.</plu> <def>A spirit believed by Muslims to inhabit
the earth and influence mankind by appearing in the form of humans or
animals. Same as <er>djinni</er> and <er>Jinnee</er>. See
<er>Jinnee</er>, <er>Jinn</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genie, jinn, jinni, jinnee, djinn, djinni.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

